    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> maybe the real problem is that there's not an easy way to use them in-memory for the duration of a task without writing them down to disk.\r\n\r\nYes! This has occurred to me as well - perhaps there's a way to virtualize the artifacts and have an 'in-memory' mode. And some `save` methods. \r\n\r\nI would actually prefer to stop modifying contracts or saving artifacts at all. Ideally the way forward for coverage is to rely on the EVM tracing engine here for source location data, rather than injecting traceable statements into people's Solidity code. \r\n\r\nIf #1035 can be resolved and it becomes clear that the stack trace can follow the execution path everywhere, I think it would make most sense on my end to migrate coverage in that direction. It's a much simpler, faster design.\r\n\r\nHowever, maybe there are other applications which would benefit from virtualized artifacts, not sure.    \r\n",
